text.text: A Guide to Fulham & Parsons Green

text.html: It's hard to think of Fulham these days without images of Made in Chelsea springing to mind: bland people with money being bland, basically. That said, we can't be generalising now can we? No, of course not, and the pretty well-to-do ends of Fulham and Parsons Green definitely pack a few surprise punches, whether it's authentic mediterranean food or real, neighbourly camaraderie. There are some lovely spots around here (and some terrible ones, but we didn't include those), so it only seems fitting to have it large. If you insist.

Fulham
Best forâ€¦ cosy neighbourhood vibin'

tip.text:
There's nothing like a good neighbourhood restaurant to have you feeling warm and cosy in your neck of the woods, which is why the people of Fulham should count themselves lucky re: Megan's. Whether you're after tasty deli delights or a sit-down meal in the lovely back garden, this is the homely spot to see about that.

Drawing inspiration from mediterranean cuisine, food offerings include the likes of deconstructed lamb or falafel kebabs and grilled swordfish with roasted vegetables. Fulham might have a reputation for being pricey, but the Â£1 (goes to charity) Monday BYOB at Megan's is a deal if ever we've seen one around town.

text.text: We love a neighbourhood restaurant. Yâ€™know, pop down in your socks and jim jams, bump into that nice family from over the road, eavesdrop on local gossip - all that jazz. Swing by in the morning for a coffee and sandwich to go or get dressed up and have yourself a romantic dinner under the fairy lights and vines out back; either way Meganâ€™s most definitely has your back. Heck, theyâ€™ll even be throwing your local BBQs here over the summer.
Best forâ€¦ getting yourself well lubricated

tip.text:
The Tommy Tucker is a pub with a bit of character about it. From the wood panelling reclaimed from an old train station, to the fresh zinc bar serving as the room's focal point and the 'Esso Lubrication Service' sign hanging above said bar. These good folk will see to your beak's wetting with a range of beers, including the bespoke 'Tommy Tucker Pale Ale.'

Drinks aside, these guys ain't messing when it comes to food either. We got well and truly involved in the baby back ribs (because no explanation needed), before sampling the more delicate venison carpaccio and grilled mackerel respectively. Delish. Get down whenever you fancy - there'll always be something to tickle your tum, but book ahead for Sunday lunches.

text.text: Itâ€™s getting harder and harder to parse gastropubs from one another: itâ€™s all gotten very serious all of a sudden, but The Tommy Tucker manage to muster a laid-back, playful vibe while doing what they do well. The â€˜Esso Lubrication Serviceâ€™ sign hung above the bar is an indicator - these guys will make sure you leave here well quenched of thirst, while thereâ€™s nothing laid-back about the approach to making good food. Make like Tommy and Tuck-er in.
Best forâ€¦ Australia by day, Italy by night

tip.text:
Artisan Australian coffee and tasty Italian treats are the doctor's order at Shot Espresso, where two worlds collide in this tiny, cosy spot in SW6. The size of the place probably means you'll do a lot of bumping into other locals while you're here, but then isn't that what you want?

Tuck into simple but fresh breakfast and brunch bites in the daytime before Shot Espresso becomes an evening aperitivo bar, dishing up Italian quiches and sharing bites to ex-pats and native Londoners alike. Buy a drink and drop Â£3 for all you can eat goodness (P.S. the aperol spritz is a no-brainer at Â£5.50). Don't be surprised to find friendly Italians spilling over from Ice & Slice over the road.

text.text: Shot Espresso is two-faced in the best kind of way; it presents two great services in the package of one cosy little cafe. Drawing from two cultures (Australia and Italy respectively), you can expect to find delicious coffee and snacks from down under in the AM, while the later afternoon and early evening vibe mirrors that of an Italian aperitivo bar. Think along the lines of affordable sharing plates, cheap Aperol spritzes (Â£5.50) and the musical, Italian voices of SW6.
Best forâ€¦ having a bit of fun down the pub

tip.text:
This is definitely a fun pub. Just down the road from Chelsea's Stamford Bridge stadium, The Cock Tavern are adding a splash of colour and personality to the North End Road: themed quizzes, swing-chairs and a generally eclectic interior design theme make for an interesting, retro vibe.

If you're thirsty you'll find plenty of ales on the taps and cans of craft in the fridge - it's difficult to ignore the colourful Beavertown designs, while there's food for the hungry too. The Bermondsey bombs (minced pork in a fried ball of mash) are pretty tasty, while the beef sliders do the job without being too exciting. Nice garden too, so expect them to throw parties over the summer.

text.text: People were calling Fulham boring so it only went and got its Cock out. This lot definitely arenâ€™t taking themselves too seriously and we can appreciate that. Youâ€™ll find plenty in the way of colour, quirky furniture (a swing-seat, yay!) and curious characters in the Cock Tavern. We stumbled across an ex-serviceman aiming to be the next poet laureate. Swing by: who knows whatâ€™ll go down but itâ€™ll probs be fun. Themed quiz anyone?
Parsons Green
Best forâ€¦ the true gastropub experience

tip.text:
Reclaimed wood, distressed mirrors, worn leather upholstery: it might sound a tad shabby but trust, The Brown Cow is far from that. These guys want to be your home away form home, which explains the lived-in feel, and even go as far as offering neighbourhood newcomers a free glass or meal as they get to know their neighbours.

You won't find these guys dabbling in the craft scene but you won't struggle to quench your thirst - cask ales, wines and cocktails are all knocking about in here. On top of that the fresh, seasonal food is just next level - that short rib of beef though...; do yourself a favour and investigate.

text.text: Now this is a delight. The space is large and airy, the second hand wooden furniture is beautiful and the food is fuckinâ€™ A. A resolutely local pub, all smiles and open arms (neighbourhood newcomers are often treated to a meal on the house), donâ€™t be surprised to catch the likes of Made in Chelsea characters enjoying a cheeky tipple here. The short rib of beef is nothing short of sensational. This is not a drill. Go and put that inside you. Thank us later.
Best forâ€¦ a bright splash of Southern Italy

tip.text:
You definitely need a dose of this bright, colourful and airy Southern Italian joint in your life. If authentic Southern Italian cuisine (Puglia, to be exact) doesn't pique your interest somewhat then there's something a bit wrong. Ingredients come from the motherland herself, while the walls are lined with wine bottles, making for interesting interior design.

What do you eat? Well, that's never gonna be easy to decide in a spot like this, but the 'Pasta Chef' dish changes on a daily basis, according to what the big man can get his hands on in the markets. Wash your dish of choice down with some fine Italian wine or, if the sun's shining, a seriously refreshing aperol spritz. When in Rome...

text.text: Sure, Parsons Green is exotic (lol), but what about Puglia? Thatâ€™s Southern Italy for you map-less Marthas out there, and Gola is bringing a bright and authentic slice of the region to SW London. Regional dishes made with fresh, market produce: bella! The â€˜Pasta Chefâ€™ is a surprise package, and changes depending on what the big man can find. P.S. the aperol spritz is well delish and refreshing. P.P.S. book ahead.
Best for...a healthy, Californian style hangout

tip.text: If Gwyneth Paltrow were a cafÃ© sheâ€™d probably look a bit like Hally's. All white wash walls, pastel interiors and organic produce, this Californian inspired cafÃ© serves healthy lunches, fresh juices and banging breakfasts. Go barefoot and sun-kissed for colourful salads, moreish muesli (yes really) and organic Monmouth coffee.

text.text: Hally's, and sister venue Little H across the road, are all about that Californian healthy hangout aesthetic. Think white wash walls, pastel interiors and organic produce that'll make you feel like a yummy mummy about to hike up the LA hills. And you're gonna see a fair few of them here. Go here for healthy lunches, fresh juices and banging breakfasts. Organic Monouth coffee should also put that pep into your step
Best forâ€¦ beer garden boozin'

tip.text:
With a neighbourhood pub atmosphere, bustling patio, and picturesque dining room, this place is one of Fulham's unhidden gems. A beer list of over 60, complimented by a knowledgable staff who let you taste before deciding, it's the kind of place where a few afternoon pints to turns into a full on dinner and lashup.

The menu offers traditional English pub food plus some veggie-friendly options. On our visit, the chicken, leek and ham hock pie, had a perfect crust and the braised carrots cooked in orange juice and ginger made a nice change. Although the desserts are tempting, it was too easy to get lost in the never ending beer list - try the sweet Belgium Duchesse de Bourgogne instead.

text.text: With a beer garden out front that overlooks Parsons Green you can bet the White Horse gets pretty rammo in the summer. Chuck in a couple BBQs and youâ€™ve got yourself a riot. Handy that this is one of the most spacious public houses youâ€™re likely to come across - at 400 years old it might be one of the oldest too. The White Horse is that trusty local boozer every self-respecting ends deserves: please admire the gleaming, brass tank of Pilsner Urquell sitting opposite the bar. Admire, then drink.
Best forâ€¦ champerzzzzz

tip.text:
Wondering where SW6's young and beautiful hang out? Look no further, 'cos this champagne bar has probably seen more red chinos than we've had hot dinners (we've had a lot). If you're looking to get a bit lively in Parsons Green then this is the spot for you - live music on weekends and bespoke cocktails make for a dangerously fun recipe.

The espresso martini is a firm fan favourite, while the champagne mojito is the signature drink here. Feeling a bit hot? Park up in the little garden and catch a breeze.

text.text: This is where the young and beautiful of Parsons Green pop bottles of champers and wet their lips on espresso martinis. As you can imagine, this spot gets pretty live and kickinâ€™ come weekends, what with live music and all that jazz. Probably not jazz. Got a bit of a squad with you? May as well book the private bit by the garden and prepare yourselves for a slippery oneâ€¦
Best forâ€¦ fine dining on the low key

tip.text:
The interior is simple, the menu is simple, the objective is simple: extremely high quality food in a laid back, unpretentious setting. Claude's Kitchen manages to create a cosy vibe, and you can bet your ass that this is a hot dating spot for the romantics of SW6.

4 starters, 4 mains. Claude switches the menu up on a weekly basis here but can guarantee inventiveness and freshness in equal measure, whether it's lamb rump w/ shrimp or wood pigeon w/ cherry and radish. The 7 course taster will set you back around Â£55, while the wine list features both progressive and vintage bottles.

text.text: It might be called Claudeâ€™s Kitchen, but the vibe in this cosy restaurant on top of Amuse Bouche is more like Claudeâ€™s Living Room: homely, understated and mellow. Grab a seat on an old school chair and prepare yourself for a quick education in fine dining (at a very reasonable price). The menu changes on a daily basis so definitely expect the unexpected.
